TY  - JOUR
AB  - The failure of contemporary economic statesmanship, of which the "depression" has made up painfully aware, was inevitable. The material realities of our civilization have never been controlled by pecuniary policies. What is required to make this clear is a clearer perception than we have enjoyed hitherto of the essential continuity of price theory--its perennial indirection and speciousness--throughout the period of "capitalist" development. Thus it begins as a mediaeval abstraction and a technique for attacking burgher power by indirection. With burgher ascendency it appears with reversed effect as the dialectic of burgher ascendency. With the reversal of mercantilist policies the pecuniary logic is once more reversed, becoming the dialectic of "free competition." But the circumstances which alone brought about the reversal of mercantilist policy and the ascendency of laissez-faire theory have worked themselves out in a situation which at last require the complete abandonment of the pecuniary illusion.
AU  - Ayres, C. E.
C1  - Full publication date: Jun., 1933
DB  - JSTOR
